  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding money laundering prevention. These typically include:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verify customer identities\n- Conduct background checks\n- Assess risk levels of customers\n\n2. Reporting requirements\n- File Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Report large cash transactions\n- Disclose potentially suspicious financial activities\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Develop internal policies and procedures\n- Conduct regular staff training\n- Implement monitoring systems\n\n4. Record keeping\n- Maintain detailed transaction records\n- Preserve documentation for specified periods\n- Enable potential investigations\n\n5. Customer due diligence\n- Perform ongoing monitoring\n- Identify potential red flags\n- Assess transaction patterns\n\n6. Regulatory compliance\n- Follow guidelines from agencies like FinCEN\n- Adhere to international standards\n- Implement risk-based approaches\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent criminals from using financial systems to hide or launder illegal funds. Non-compliance can result in significant legal penalties, fines, and potential criminal charges for financial institutions.\n\nMost countries have specific legal frameworks establishing these requirements, with variations in precise implementation.",
